<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-052-122 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 415 263</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Sept 30 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Multifunction peripherals common in future, says analyst. (RobAuster of BIS Strategic Decisions)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Buckler, Grant.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ForecastingMultifunctionalPeripheralsMultitaskingFuture of Computing.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>****Multifunction Peripherals Common In Future, Says Analyst 09/30/91VANCOUVER, WASHINGTON, U.S.A., 1991 SEP 30 (NB) -- Printer, facsimile,scanner, and copier vendors searching for new ways to lure customers willproduce a wave of multifunction machines that print, fax, scan, and copy inthe next few years, according to Rob Auster, group director of electronicprinting at BIS Strategic Decisions of Norwell, Massachusetts.andP;  Auster wasspeaking to a gathering of international journalists here, sponsored byHewlett-Packard.andM;&quot;Single-function vendors are basically running out of room to grow,&quot; Austersaid.andP;  Rather than compete on price, the vendors want to add features totheir products.andP;  In the search for new features to add, he predicted, theywill turn single-function units into multi-function units.andM;Auster said customers will buy the multifunction machines because the conceptis easy to understand and because they will believe they are getting more fortheir money.andP;  &quot;Eighty percent of what we buy in life is perception, notreality,&quot; he said.andM;There are concerns about multifunction devices, Auster admitted.andP;  One is thatif you rely on one machine for several functions, when that machine breakseverything is out of service.andP;  Auster said vendors can combat this byemphasizing the multifunction unit's relationship to reliable laser printersrather than to less reliable photocopiers and fax machines.andM;Customers may also worry that relying on one machine for several functionswill mean long lineups to use it and problems with, for instance, receivingincoming faxes while the machine is printing a document.andP;  Built-in memory andmultitasking features can help get around this objection, Auster said.andM;He added that the rise of multifunction machines could create a boom incertain computer applications that rely on devices such as scanners.andP;  As moreand more computer users buy multifunction peripherals and thus get scannersthey might not have bought separately, they will be more inclined to look atscanning-related applications such as optical character recognition, Austersaid.andM;Hewlett-Packard officials were cautious about Auster's projections.andP;  &quot;I agreewith him that there's going to be a multifunction business,&quot; said BillMcGlynn of HP's printer products group, &quot;but I don't think it's going to beas big as he thinks it is.&quot;andM;McGlynn suggested customers may be more interested buying products that letthem add the functions they want as extra modules rather than paying all atonce for units that do everything.andM;However, another HP official, while calling the future of multifunctiondevices &quot;debatable,&quot; said it is inevitable the company will offermultifunction products.andM;(Grant Buckler/19910930)</TEXT></DOC>